Plotting with ggplot2

Esko

29.06.2016

Dataset

We will load the dataset created in section Merging two data frames, where we had game performance and working memory test data.

game.wmc <- read.table("kr_gamewmc.txt", header=T)

# and let's calculate accuracy again
game.wmc$accuracy <- game.wmc$Phit + game.wmc$PcorrectRejection

ggplot2 package

The built-in plotting commands in R are powerful, but may not be very intuitive to use. Luckily, there are many packages which provide alternative ways for plotting data. ggplot2 is one of my favorites.

The basic idea is simple: First you map the variable of the data frame to elements of the plot. Then you “add” different representation or “layers” to the plot.

First, there are example which replicate some previous plots with ggplot2.

In order to visualize an association between two continous variables, a scatter plot would be perfect.

require(ggplot2)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=pcu_score, y=accuracy)) + geom_point() 
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (geom_point).

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=pcu_score, y=accuracy)) + geom_point(size=4) 
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (geom_point).

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=pcu_score, y=accuracy)) + geom_point(size=4, colour="blue") 
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (geom_point).

Let’s first add some more mapping between aesthetics and data. Add mapping to colour…

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=pcu_score, y=accuracy, colour=age_grp)) + 
  geom_point() 
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (geom_point).

… and shape.

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=pcu_score, y=accuracy, colour=age_grp, shape=age_grp)) + 
  geom_point() 
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (geom_point).

Next we can add a new layer. geom_smooth with paramter method=“lm” will fit a regression line to data.

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=pcu_score, y=accuracy)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm")
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (stat_smooth).
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (geom_point).

If we define here colour and/or shape, smoothing is done separately for each grouping aesthetics like colour and shape.

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=pcu_score, y=accuracy, colour=age_grp, shape=age_grp)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm")
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (stat_smooth).
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (geom_point).

If we wish, we can override this by defining group=1.

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=pcu_score, y=accuracy, colour=age_grp, shape=age_grp, group=1)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm")
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (stat_smooth).
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 1 rows containing missing values
## (geom_point).

Boxplots

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=age_grp, y=accuracy, colour=age_grp)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

Mean and CI

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=age_grp, y=accuracy, colour=age_grp)) + 
  stat_summary(fun.data="mean_cl_normal", size=2)

Histogram and density

Note how we need to change the mapping between variables and plot objects accordingly.

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=accuracy)) + 
  geom_histogram()

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=accuracy)) + 
  geom_density()

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=accuracy, colour=age_grp)) + 
  geom_density()

Making two plots using a grouping variable

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=pcu_score, fill=age_grp)) + 
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_grid(age_grp ~ .)

ggplot(game.wmc, aes(x=pcu_score, fill=age_grp)) + 
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_grid(. ~ age_grp)
